( well that was the plan ) We both liked the look of Grau Douro from the reviews and found the establishment very easily in Rua Dunques de Braganca. On arrival the small (but cosy) place was very busy and having no booking we were offered a seat at the bar.This offer was accepted and the owner came straight over with the drinks menu , we are not knowledgeable about Portuguese wine so asked for some guidance. He asked what we liked and suggested a couple of wines ( neither were expensive) and promptly poured a taste of each, followed by a full measure. We quaffed the lovely wine ordered some more and asked for the food menu. The owner who was clearly in control of the whole show was exhilarating to watch , moving from table to table , laughing and joking with the customers and even playing the accordion from time to time a delight to observe. The food arrived Covert ( bread with oil ) the Prawns in garlic sauce and a portion of Bacalhau a bras (codfish , slices of potato and egg cooked in the oven) both dishes were absolutely delicious. Unfortunately by siting at the bar the Toucinho do Ceo do Avo ( Grandpa`s Heavenly Tart ) was positioned on the bar top just in front of us , so a portion along with a very nice glass of port had to be consumed to finish the night. Everything about the place is fantastic, the food is amazing , the staff are friendly and great , the atmosphere is homely , all in all a great find , needless to say we only managed the one bar that night best laid plans and all that. Grau Douro thankyou for a Fantastic Evening. We will be back.

review_data.review_title: Need to bring ID if not staying at the hostel
review_data.review: We visited last Friday evening.  The night didn't start off well as the security guard watching the motorbikes told us we couldn't come in because my husband is Khmer.  I started to feel my blood boil but luckily another staff member came and said we could come in but we had to go talk to reception (we weren't planning on staying, we just wanted dinner and a drink)  At reception, a lady who was a bit more knowledgeable than the security guard explained that since you have to walk past all the hostel rooms (3 floors) to get to the Sky bar where the bar/restaurant is, they need to take a copy of ID cards for Khmers and a copy of the photo page in the passport for non-Khmers to know who is coming and going for the safety and security of the guests at the hostel.  Once this was explained properly in a polite manner it was not a problem. I still find it a bit strange though as I normally don't carry around my passport when going out for dinner but luckily hubby had his ID card which meant that he became a member and could bring in a guest, me. So, it all worked out ok in the end. It's just a shame that the new security guard (we were told he was new by the other member of staff) is turning locals away.  As with most things here, it is an easily solvable problem. I don't know why they can't put up a big poster saying "ID card (for Cambodians) or passport (for non-Cambodians) needed to enter the premises for the safety and security of guests and visitors. We appreciate your co-operation."  After all, they had a poster saying their restaurant was closed but still welcome to order food at the bar, so they are capable of making and putting up signs.  The food was surprisingly good for a hostel. It was No.1 on TripAdvisor about a month ago and I was curious about it so suggested to my husband that we go.  Luckily, the nice female member of staff (didn't catch her name) and the good food managed to turn the evening around but just be forewarned that if you're not a guest you'll need ID to be able to go into the bar/restaurant area.

review_data.review_title: Mostly good but room for improvement
review_data.review: I visited twice in December, once by myself for lunch and again for lunch with hubby.  The first time I visited I had to go to the counter to ask for a menu. I sat down thinking they would bring a menu but I changed tables as I was too hot where I originally sat down. I wasn’t brought a menu at either table so I thought they didn’t have table service and you had to order at the counter by the cakes. When I asked if I could see their lunch menu they said they’d bring it over. Perhaps they didn’t see me come in but my first impression wasn’t that good. I know it’s not a big thing but nevertheless it’s nice to be greeted and brought a menu within the first few mins of entering a cafe/restaurant. Perhaps it would be better just to leave the menus on the table.  On my first visit they had run out of the vegan quiche. I understand cafes run out of food but it was a little bit disappointing since it was only around 1pm which is peak lunch time. Luckily, I’m not vegan I just like to eat vegan sometimes but from memory there weren’t that many other vegan choices so this may be a problem for others.  On my 2nd visit I was able to order the vegan quiche and my husband ordered a veggie one. Unfortunately, the vegan quiche had mustard seed and I’m allergic to mustard so I had to swap with my husband. It wasn’t written on the menu so I didn’t know before ordering. It would be nice if this info was added to the menu. I took one bite before I realized. The vegan quiche was not as tasty as the veggie quiche which contains dairy so perhaps a little tweak of the recipe might be in order.  We ordered 2 coconuts and one was nice and chilled and the other one completely warm.  On the 2nd visit we were brought menus straight away but our waitress silently took our order and also didn’t say anything when she brought our bill which my husband commented on. He thought perhaps she didn’t speak English. My husband is a local so she could have used Khmer if she preferred.  I understand this is a training school cafe so I’m writing this as constructive feedback so that others can have a more seamless experience.  The points above wouldn’t stop me from visiting again but there’s room for improvement.

review_data.review: Just around the corner from our hotel, this restaurant is absolutely beautiful. The furniture and décor are a sight to behold. Low lighting at night makes it a very romantic evening. Fo0d was delicious although took a little while to arrive. Would go there again.

In Paris, the competition in the fine dining category is fierce.  It’s as if every night is a playoff game and everyone is gunning for the title. Here, a Michelin Star might actually be worth more than in other cities. And if you’re lucky enough to be on vacation, with back-to-back dinners at this level, you would imagine that someone has to lose. It was with this pressure we dined at Pur, having just experienced newly starred Saturne the night before.  Would there be space for its unique take on starred excellence?  Pur is a classic fine dining experience. This is not a let down. Imagine the finest ingredients in unique combinations. Now imagine them served at a level that take six dishes and create wonderful arc.  While identifying individual dishes is useless as Chef Aie Okabayashi is sure to adjust the menu based on what’s seasonal, the one prevailing taste we encountered was “smoke”. Similar to the essence of barbecue, there were hits of smoke and wood in unexpected delicate places like fish. Yes there was a duck course that was one of the best…the skin by alone could have been a delicacy.  Lest we forget, two of the six courses were desserts, with a palate cleanser that could be a dish in itself. Actually, the that cleaner tart “soufflé” was probably our favorite, and the pastry chef, who busily prepped dishes all night next to our chef’s table, humbly admitted it was his as well.  We opted not to commit to the wine pairings, but the Sancerre and Margeux by the glass were excellent. If you prefer cocktails, their take on the Moscow Mule is worth the price. And don’t be intimidated by the six-courses. It’s the right size and takes about three hours, so it was well-paced.  Finally, the service was superb. It doesn’t hurt that we were seated at the chef’s table with a window into the kitchen where Chef was making sure no detail was overlooked. And yes she made one trainee remake a simple amuse-bouche simply because he failed to sprinkle the dust in the right direction. And an anniversary cake for a couple celebrating theirs was reset because it sat a few minutes too long.  Situated in the sexy Park Hyatt Vendome, this is far more than a “hotel” restaurant. It’s epic…they brought their A-game on an average Tuesday evening. But hey, this is Paris, and the next Michelin wannabe is right around the corner!  The good news is that Pur has the goods, elegance and fine creations, to keep that star shining.

The food is over the top good. “That’s the best chicken satay I’ve ever had.” “The schnitzel is awesome,” and we’ve lived in Germany. “The curry is frickin great, why cant they have a ‘all you can eat menu?’” OK. That wasn’t actually said but I did think it. The deserts were awesome as well. And what the owners/directors are doing for young Cambodians is worthy of your patronage and a healthy tip.

We had dinner Good Friday Booked a table online fee weeks prior to visiting queenstown! Small and cosy restaurant great service and atmosphere! So many locals recommended the restaurant Simple wine list and great food Good with kids totally recommend this restaurant happy to return!

We loved our experience at Baoli Bao. The burgers are so unique. The buns are great. Everything we tried was delicious. Please go here and explore the creativity of their menu. The service was quick and kind.

review_data.review_title: This restaurant must have one of the best views in the world and good food to match
review_data.review: I can't tell you how impressed we were by this restaurant. The views over the Bosphorus and the Golden Horne were breathtaking. The staff were helpful and the food good and not expensive. The menu is typically Turkish. Highly recommended.
The food was really nice here, but I particularly want to mention the service here which was the best we had in Ubud. Lovely people with good food and the price was reasonable too.

The menu is reasonably extensive and interesting. There are lots of good dishes to choose from. They have "swing" tables which are pretty unique - and pretty relaxing as it turned out.  All of the food was elevated, this is a gourmet experience. Enjoyed the pumpkin soup and the had a mushroom noodle dish that was delicious. Service was spot on.  Highly recommended for more of a fine dining experience.

This place offered elevated traditional Khmer food in a beautiful environment. Some of the tables are on swings which made you feel like you were floating. This was the best meal we had in Siem Reap. We met the chef, who it turns out has worked at some gourmet International restaurants which explains the quality and "fusion twist".  Highly recommend.

This place is a ripper. Really recommend booking in advance as we sat in the front window area and watched countless walkup people turned away due to capacity. Bella Cucina is only a small restaurant with the kitchen/pizza oven centre to the room. The menu changes almost daily to some extent, and is not extensive but covers you for choice nicely. Don't load up on bread first (the garlic bread is a pizza size) as the main dishes are plentiful servings. Gnocchi was terrific. Dessert of tiramisu was excellent. The staff member at reception and serving tables was so calm, unflustered and efficient, always with a smile despite the constant queue of people out the door. Would definitely recommend and return.

A very busy little side street restaurant. Bookings in advance essential due to popularity and size of restaurant. We chose the "chef's choice" offer of 7 courses and each was fresh, tasty and diverse. Staff were efficient and helpful.

review_data.review_title: Great atmosphere and food, lovely staff and all for a good cause. What more can you want?
review_data.review: I am a frequent customer (have been living in Siem Reap for a year) and this place is a great place to go for a bit of piece and quiet away from the usual noise in Siem Reap.  The food is great (I am vegan and they do have a vegan brunch, or a smoothie bowl) ) and the staff very pleasant and helpful.  If you are into the pastry/sweet cakes there is a lot of choice and everything is made fresh on the premises.  They also often have freshly made jam and peanut butter - certainly worth buying to take with you.  You can also order bread (the day before) which is freshly baked on the premises - and its healthy as well!  Bayon Pastry School is a training facility for girls/women who would otherwise struggle to get a reasonable job. Here they are taught the fine art of making pastries, cakes etc. and then have a great start to getting a decent paying job at the end of their 12 months training.

My wife and I throughly enjoyed our evening. A big thank you to Giuseppe our waiter for the evening who we found out was the restaurant manager.  We preordered halal so lamb was available for us which was wow.  The halibut fish was perfection and now the Soufflé was something else. The pistachio flavours making it a treat.  The starters we had the celeriac and the lobster which were a delight. the rosemary bread was soft and warm.  The service was fantastic friendly and very attentive.  Overall, I highly recommend this place for a beautiful couples dinner or a business lunch.
Not really anything negative to say here. The food was fantastic and well priced. Noodles were amazing and the dumplings even better. Staff were polite and attentive. Would visit again!
I visited restaurant on lunch time and ordered Paneer kadai and it was excellent. Garlic naan was good. Salted lassi is also good.  i will recommended this restaurant in Prague for vegetarians.
We took buffet menu and it was great, Food was awesome and excellant taste. Dal was excellent, taste was good.

Visited this place on my recent trip to Prague. Located near old town and the restaurant is in the basement. Decent place and we ordered our dishes as well as butter chicken. It tasted nothing like butter chicken and we told the manager about it. I appreciate the fact that they listened to our complain and acknowledged the same. They also took of the charges off our final bill. Other then this everything else was good. Service also has a scope for improvement. Overall I would recommend this place for Indian food.

review_data.review_title: Fab cocktails in a nice garden setting
review_data.review: The cocktails at Wild are really fab. They don’t do dinner as such but have many different types of spring rolls. So, it’s like tapas. We ordered 5 lots of different spring rolls between the 2 of us and found that to be enough for dinner. We also tried 3 different cocktails, all of which were good. The garden setting is really lovely and I can’t wait to visit again.

review_data.review_title: Mostly good but room for improvement
review_data.review: I visited twice in December, once by myself for lunch and again for lunch with hubby.  The first time I visited I had to go to the counter to ask for a menu. I sat down thinking they would bring a menu but I changed tables as I was too hot where I originally sat down. I wasn’t brought a menu at either table so I thought they didn’t have table service and you had to order at the counter by the cakes. When I asked if I could see their lunch menu they said they’d bring it over. Perhaps they didn’t see me come in but my first impression wasn’t that good. I know it’s not a big thing but nevertheless it’s nice to be greeted and brought a menu within the first few mins of entering a cafe/restaurant. Perhaps it would be better just to leave the menus on the table.  On my first visit they had run out of the vegan quiche. I understand cafes run out of food but it was a little bit disappointing since it was only around 1pm which is peak lunch time. Luckily, I’m not vegan I just like to eat vegan sometimes but from memory there weren’t that many other vegan choices so this may be a problem for others.  On my 2nd visit I was able to order the vegan quiche and my husband ordered a veggie one. Unfortunately, the vegan quiche had mustard seed and I’m allergic to mustard so I had to swap with my husband. It wasn’t written on the menu so I didn’t know before ordering. It would be nice if this info was added to the menu. I took one bite before I realized. The vegan quiche was not as tasty as the veggie quiche which contains dairy so perhaps a little tweak of the recipe might be in order.  We ordered 2 coconuts and one was nice and chilled and the other one completely warm.  On the 2nd visit we were brought menus straight away but our waitress silently took our order and also didn’t say anything when she brought our bill which my husband commented on. He thought perhaps she didn’t speak English. My husband is a local so she could have used Khmer if she preferred.  I understand this is a training school cafe so I’m writing this as constructive feedback so that others can have a more seamless experience.  The points above wouldn’t stop me from visiting again but there’s room for improvement.

review_data.review_title: Not many choices for lunch but the choices they do have are tasty
review_data.review: The only choices for the mains is cold pasta. I wasn’t sure what I’d think of the mango pasta but it wasn’t too sweet and great as a main dish.

review_data.review_title: Business lunch menu is superb value for money
review_data.review: I visited Chi restaurant with my cousin and his wife for lunch. We ordered from the business lunch menu. It is extremely good value for money considering the quality of food, ambience and service.  You can get 2 courses for $12 or 3 courses for $15 including one glass of wine or a soft drink. I found out about the business lunch menu from other TA reviews.  Unfortunately, we couldn’t afford to visit Chi restaurant for tasting menus that they offer in the evening but this was perfect.  The manager Sarah even came to introduce herself during our meal.  I would definitely like to visit again with hubby.

Hubby and I decided to try this new cafe since I noticed it was getting a lot of good reviews. The service was good without being overbearing and the staff checked with us if the food was ok.  They have a good selection of Khmer and Western food as well as juices and coffees. 2 mains and a green juice set us back $11.50 which I think was reasonable given the portion size and quality of the food. I would like to visit again, it’s just a shame it’s not open later on in the evening.

My husband and I had dinner here 2 nights ago. The ambience and presentation of the food was nice but the colourful sauces were more for decorative purposes than for taste which was a shame. Maybe it just wasn't to our taste.  The chive dumpling dish was better but the sauce for the veggies was so spicy it was a struggle to finish the dish.

review_data.review_title: Reasonably priced food in a beautiful garden setting
review_data.review: The price of the food was reasonable considering the beautiful setting of the restaurant. $10.50 for 2 meals and a drink. We were served fairly quickly and the service was friendly. I would definitely visit again.

review_data.review_title: Need to bring ID if not staying at the hostel
review_data.review: We visited last Friday evening.  The night didn't start off well as the security guard watching the motorbikes told us we couldn't come in because my husband is Khmer.  I started to feel my blood boil but luckily another staff member came and said we could come in but we had to go talk to reception (we weren't planning on staying, we just wanted dinner and a drink)  At reception, a lady who was a bit more knowledgeable than the security guard explained that since you have to walk past all the hostel rooms (3 floors) to get to the Sky bar where the bar/restaurant is, they need to take a copy of ID cards for Khmers and a copy of the photo page in the passport for non-Khmers to know who is coming and going for the safety and security of the guests at the hostel.  Once this was explained properly in a polite manner it was not a problem. I still find it a bit strange though as I normally don't carry around my passport when going out for dinner but luckily hubby had his ID card which meant that he became a member and could bring in a guest, me. So, it all worked out ok in the end. It's just a shame that the new security guard (we were told he was new by the other member of staff) is turning locals away.  As with most things here, it is an easily solvable problem. I don't know why they can't put up a big poster saying "ID card (for Cambodians) or passport (for non-Cambodians) needed to enter the premises for the safety and security of guests and visitors. We appreciate your co-operation."  After all, they had a poster saying their restaurant was closed but still welcome to order food at the bar, so they are capable of making and putting up signs.  The food was surprisingly good for a hostel. It was No.1 on TripAdvisor about a month ago and I was curious about it so suggested to my husband that we go.  Luckily, the nice female member of staff (didn't catch her name) and the good food managed to turn the evening around but just be forewarned that if you're not a guest you'll need ID to be able to go into the bar/restaurant area.

review_data.review_title: Tasty new Indian restaurant in town
review_data.review: I decided to visit based on the other positive reviews and to check out the new Indian restaurant in town. I am a big fan of paneer dishes. I ordered the paneer tikka masala which was delicious and they were generous with the paneer which I appreciated. The mango lassi was also very tasty. Pricing is similar to other Indian restaurants in town but I would say Rasoi Ghar is one of the better Indian restaurants that I’ve tried in Siem Reap and I’ve tried a fair few.

review_data.review_title: Best Greek food outside of Greece and better than most inside

A wonderful tasty meal, super friendly staff, great atmosphere, super clean. A absolute gem of a place. I traveled a four hour round trip just to eat here and well worth it. Will I return again you bet I will.

Domenico’s is a nice change of pace restaurant in a cool neighborhood in Paris in the 9th district. The staff ensured we were sat early as we had a show to attend. The meal was good Italian food with the only slight negative being a limited menu. Pasta dishes were plentiful. The truffle pasta is highly recommended.

review_data.review_title: Bargain café at Petticoat Lane Market
review_data.review: There’s nothing to beat a good old-fashioned Full English Breakfast. Here at Café Nora (formerly Café Thyme), there are nine fry-ups to choose from, ranging from £6.95 to £7.95, all cooked to order and served with tea or freshly ground coffee and toast or bread. The English Breakfast of two eggs, two rashers of bacon, sausage, hash browns, baked beans, mushroom, black pudding and grilled tomatoes is a firm favourite. There’s also a Mediterranean Set Breakfast and Vegan Brunch with vegan sausage and avocado. For the more adventurous, there is Eggs Benedict, omelettes, pastas, salads, pancakes, burgers, panini, jacket potatoes, sandwiches and filled baguettes. Something for everyone. Situated in East London’s popular Petticoat Lane Market, on Wentworth Street and near the corner of Middlesex Street, the café is run by Turkish chef Ebru Puleri and her female Turkish friends. It’s a friendly, warm place, with comfortable seating, and popular with local workers, neighbours, market traders, students and visitors to London. It is walking distance from Aldgate East Tube and Liverpool Street Station. Open daily from early morning to 3pm.

Managed to get a late lunch straight from the airport. It was a lovely day with sunshine and the outdoor seating area is ideal. It is located by the lake, just in front of Crowne Plaza hotel.  The Salmon was fantastic and the burgers pretty good. Plenty of drinks to choose from and one could spend an afternoon just hanging out there. Service was prompt and attentive. Would definitely come again.

Visited here with a group of teenage boys - no one was hungry afterwards! Ribs and steaks both very good, garlic sizzling mushrooms divine. Fairly pricey menu but on par with other similar establishments around the area.

chose to visit here knowing that the pizza and pasta were housemade and therefore no GF options available. however there were plenty of other options and i had a divine squid dish. great range of italian wines and the smells from the pizza oven were sensational!!!

Such a lovely welcome we received! We were greeted like long lost friends on our first visit. We won’t go anywhere else when we are back in London! Thank you both so very much!

The food is great but what really makes this this place is the incredible staff and the warm welcome. This was our first visit to Theo Raandall and we thoroughly enjoyed it. My partner had the Sicilian set menu with wine pairings and I ate from the a la carte. review_data.review_title: A little if the beaten track but well worth the visit
review_data.review: We had dinner here in the suburbs of Prague. Lovely restaurant, tables well spaced, nice welcome. The service was very good, even though they were full. The food was excellent and the wines (including imported) and other drinks reasonably priced. All the starters were delicious and we can recommend the “shared” all starter plate. The foie gras starter was special. Best if the mains for us was the calf cheeks.

We stayed at the Anantara resort for our honeymoon and ate here twice.  Sea.Fire.Salt is the premier eaterie at both Anantara and Marriott. It's more of a fine dining experience than other restaurants we ate at and it's fronted by the excellent, well travelled, French maitre d', Laurant. Who's a nice guy and very informative on your food and wine if you need him to be. First time here we had the mixed seafood brick (scallops, prawn, sea bass) and the mixed grill (lamb chop, steak, chicken) bricks. The searing hot Himalayan salt bricks are maybe a little bit of artistic licence and whether or not they contribute anything other than a hot, salty brick to your meal I wouldn't know. But they do make the difference of bringing something unique and interesting to the table. Food was very good, well presented with potato and vegetable sides. Handmade Sorbet deserts are delicious. As always in Asia, red wine served chilled, why do you do that? 2nd time we ate here was the last night of our stay, because it's a very nice place and it's nice being spoiled occasionally. Outrageously juicy Wagyu and Sirloin steaks served with a selection of salts that vary in colour, texture and taste, Very nice. I spoke to front of house when I arrived and was delighted when they managed to find me a non-chilled, perfect temperature bottle of red wine to enjoy with my steak. It completed my meal and I'm grateful for the efforts that were made. Food here is certainly not cheap, but it's good. Undoubtedly you're paying a little extra for the whole outdoor, on the seafront, well presented, himalayan brick, finer experience. Which I enjoyed. And I'd eat there again. Très Bien

There's always something special about returning to Ginja Taste. Such a nice ambience with a great menu and service. From the moment we arrived and were greeted so warmly, to the end of the night before we left and the Chef came around to see if we liked what we ordered...well the plates were all empty! The soft shell salt and pepper crab and the yellow beef curry were to DIE for! Thank you Chef Tham for your gracious hospitality. We keep coming back here...keep up the fantastic standard.

review_data.review: Returned to enjoy the amazing range on offer. Breakfast goes until Noon which is great for Sunday sleep-ins. It is simply the best buffet breakfast ever! Be sure to book especially on Sunday.

review_data.review: My husband and I had dinner here 2 nights ago. The ambience and presentation of the food was nice but the colourful sauces were more for decorative purposes than for taste which was a shame. Maybe it just wasn't to our taste.  The chive dumpling dish was better but the sauce for the veggies was so spicy it was a struggle to finish the dish.

review_data.review_title: Fab cocktails in a nice garden setting
review_data.review: The cocktails at Wild are really fab. They don’t do dinner as such but have many different types of spring rolls. So, it’s like tapas. We ordered 5 lots of different spring rolls between the 2 of us and found that to be enough for dinner. We also tried 3 different cocktails, all of which were good. The garden setting is really lovely and I can’t wait to visit again.

review_data.review_title: Mostly good but room for improvement
review_data.review: I visited twice in December, once by myself for lunch and again for lunch with hubby.  The first time I visited I had to go to the counter to ask for a menu. I sat down thinking they would bring a menu but I changed tables as I was too hot where I originally sat down. I wasn’t brought a menu at either table so I thought they didn’t have table service and you had to order at the counter by the cakes. When I asked if I could see their lunch menu they said they’d bring it over. Perhaps they didn’t see me come in but my first impression wasn’t that good. I know it’s not a big thing but nevertheless it’s nice to be greeted and brought a menu within the first few mins of entering a cafe/restaurant. Perhaps it would be better just to leave the menus on the table.  On my first visit they had run out of the vegan quiche. I understand cafes run out of food but it was a little bit disappointing since it was only around 1pm which is peak lunch time. Luckily, I’m not vegan I just like to eat vegan sometimes but from memory there weren’t that many other vegan choices so this may be a problem for others.  On my 2nd visit I was able to order the vegan quiche and my husband ordered a veggie one. Unfortunately, the vegan quiche had mustard seed and I’m allergic to mustard so I had to swap with my husband. It wasn’t written on the menu so I didn’t know before ordering. It would be nice if this info was added to the menu. I took one bite before I realized. The vegan quiche was not as tasty as the veggie quiche which contains dairy so perhaps a little tweak of the recipe might be in order.  We ordered 2 coconuts and one was nice and chilled and the other one completely warm.  On the 2nd visit we were brought menus straight away but our waitress silently took our order and also didn’t say anything when she brought our bill which my husband commented on. He thought perhaps she didn’t speak English. My husband is a local so she could have used Khmer if she preferred.  I understand this is a training school cafe so I’m writing this as constructive feedback so that others can have a more seamless experience.  The points above wouldn’t stop me from visiting again but there’s room for improvement.

review_data.review_title: Not many choices for lunch but the choices they do have are tasty
review_data.review: The only choices for the mains is cold pasta. I wasn’t sure what I’d think of the mango pasta but it wasn’t too sweet and great as a main dish.

review_data.review_title: Business lunch menu is superb value for money
review_data.review: I visited Chi restaurant with my cousin and his wife for lunch. We ordered from the business lunch menu. It is extremely good value for money considering the quality of food, ambience and service.  You can get 2 courses for $12 or 3 courses for $15 including one glass of wine or a soft drink. I found out about the business lunch menu from other TA reviews.  Unfortunately, we couldn’t afford to visit Chi restaurant for tasting menus that they offer in the evening but this was perfect.  The manager Sarah even came to introduce herself during our meal.  I would definitely like to visit again with hubby.

review_data.review_title: Smooth service for the most part
review_data.review: Sala Bai is a training school so sometimes there can be a few problems. We had a problem with one of our dishes but otherwise the meal itself and the service was very good. The duty manager came to speak to us at the end of our meal to check our dining experience which I appreciated. Eating at the training restaurant allows them to continue training students and I would definitely eat there again.

Hubby and I decided to try this new cafe since I noticed it was getting a lot of good reviews. The service was good without being overbearing and the staff checked with us if the food was ok.  They have a good selection of Khmer and Western food as well as juices and coffees. 2 mains and a green juice set us back $11.50 which I think was reasonable given the portion size and quality of the food. I would like to visit again, it’s just a shame it’s not open later on in the evening.

review_data.review_title: Reasonably priced food in a beautiful garden setting
review_data.review: The price of the food was reasonable considering the beautiful setting of the restaurant. $10.50 for 2 meals and a drink. We were served fairly quickly and the service was friendly. I would definitely visit again.

review_data.review_title: Need to bring ID if not staying at the hostel
review_data.review: We visited last Friday evening.  The night didn't start off well as the security guard watching the motorbikes told us we couldn't come in because my husband is Khmer.  I started to feel my blood boil but luckily another staff member came and said we could come in but we had to go talk to reception (we weren't planning on staying, we just wanted dinner and a drink)  At reception, a lady who was a bit more knowledgeable than the security guard explained that since you have to walk past all the hostel rooms (3 floors) to get to the Sky bar where the bar/restaurant is, they need to take a copy of ID cards for Khmers and a copy of the photo page in the passport for non-Khmers to know who is coming and going for the safety and security of the guests at the hostel.  Once this was explained properly in a polite manner it was not a problem. I still find it a bit strange though as I normally don't carry around my passport when going out for dinner but luckily hubby had his ID card which meant that he became a member and could bring in a guest, me. So, it all worked out ok in the end. It's just a shame that the new security guard (we were told he was new by the other member of staff) is turning locals away.  As with most things here, it is an easily solvable problem. I don't know why they can't put up a big poster saying "ID card (for Cambodians) or passport (for non-Cambodians) needed to enter the premises for the safety and security of guests and visitors. We appreciate your co-operation."  After all, they had a poster saying their restaurant was closed but still welcome to order food at the bar, so they are capable of making and putting up signs.  The food was surprisingly good for a hostel. It was No.1 on TripAdvisor about a month ago and I was curious about it so suggested to my husband that we go.  Luckily, the nice female member of staff (didn't catch her name) and the good food managed to turn the evening around but just be forewarned that if you're not a guest you'll need ID to be able to go into the bar/restaurant area.

review_data.review_title: Tasty new Indian restaurant in town
review_data.review: I decided to visit based on the other positive reviews and to check out the new Indian restaurant in town. I am a big fan of paneer dishes. I ordered the paneer tikka masala which was delicious and they were generous with the paneer which I appreciated. The mango lassi was also very tasty. Pricing is similar to other Indian restaurants in town but I would say Rasoi Ghar is one of the better Indian restaurants that I’ve tried in Siem Reap and I’ve tried a fair few.

My kids and I were staying in Chinatown looking for great Xiao Long Bao (soup dumplings) so we stopped at Shanghai Asian Cuisine. Terrific dumplings and terrific prices. We ordered 1 order per person and some fried rice. Food was tasty and cheap. Cash only!

We ended in this little cute restaurant next to our Riad, the reviews were excellent and we definitely agree! We took “Le tajine des gazelle” with a mix of dry fruits (apricot, almond, lemon) and a traditional couscous. The plates are generous and homemade, so savoury! For 10€ you will enjoy the plenty of Marrakech. Waiters are so kind! You have to try this amazing little restaurant!
The food was absolutely delicious. Not a dingle Thing we tried was not worth the money. It was a Really nice discovery. The staff was very friendly as well. Recommended.
This is one of the set menue restaurants where you have to order a huge set menue bound to drive you into food coma, beautiful garden and nice service bit you can find much better moroccan places

Well Chef's table ...and counter and food preparation area - space is at a premium in this quirky place. It's quite small with seating for 6 or 7 at the counter/bar at the back of which the chef is preparing the food as you order it and 3 or 4 tables for 2. You could happen to be lucky and drop by but it's makes more sense to believe all the positive reviews and make a booking before you plan to go. It's a joy, the two guys and lady who run the place are really engaging and welcoming and of course, the tapas style food is tasty and good value and as the title suggests, they know their wine and are happy to make suggestions around matching.

We decided to try something different on our last trip to New York and opted for Jungsik. We opted for the signature tasting with premium wines and we were not disappointed! Each course was flavorful with premium ingredient and original presentation. Service was friendly, attentive and efficient. The wine pairing although expensive really helped bring an additional dimension to the food with the sommelier walking us through each pairing in details.  Overall we had a wonderful night at Jungsik and even though it's not as well known as some of the other high-end restaurants in New York, we highly recommend you give it a shot!

review_data.review_title: Great experience at a reasonable price
review_data.review: We made a reservation at Aspic solely based on the glowing reviews on Trip Advisor and we were not disappointed.  As others have mentioned this is a fixed menu only type of restaurants so you need to be flexible but what came out of the kitchen on the night we were there did not disappoint one bit. What was interesting is that unlike many of the other restaurants we went to during our trip to France, Aspic offered a wine pairing with the meal which was quite nice and added an extra layer to the experience.  Service was overall good but you need to go into this with the right expectation that this is a lean operation. As far as I could tell there was the chef in the kitchen and one waitress for about 12 tables. It didn't feel slow or anything but it wasn't "high touch" either.  Overall we were pleasantly surprised with the experience. When the check came in, we were even more surprised at how affordable this experience was. Given the quality and creativity, I don't think it's going to stay this way for long so you better go and enjoy it!

Close to Rue Daguerre (very food shops), the place is managed by a friendly couple. Small restaurant of about 20 seats that takes reservations. Short menu of good products well prepared. Generous portions at a reasonable price (lunch menu at 30 euros, for dinner count between 40 and 50)

The place to go in Dubai when you are out of india and longing for authentic indian fare. The service is at par and the menu is never ending, i would alert that you choose quickly else you may end up spending 30 mins looking at whole menu. The taste is good and would rate the service higher.

review_data.review_title: For entertainment, not for the food
review_data.review: I have never been much of a fan of teppanaki food for the taste as it is inevitably bland and boring. Benihana is a legend in the teppanyaki cuisine and for what it is, it’s fine. This is a place for food theatre where people go with their kids / friends for a fun evening.  Service – the service is good at this Benihana. The reception was nice and efficient and the waitresses are nice, drinks and non-teppanaki items served quickly and they did a good job with special requests on the table. Chefs were fun, engaged the kids and put on a good show for everyone.  Food – Ordered the cod with miso and a side of scallops. The fish was good enough, but the miso was added as a sauce (vs glazed on top) which was disappointing. The unique black cod taste was lost on the grill and the luscious oiliness of the fish was lost. My son ordered beef and eat everything as it was served medium so soft to eat in bite size pieces so he liked it. I am not a fan of the food and only attended on the request of my son.  Value – teppanyaki is always expensive. My young son and I had 2 mains, 1 starter and a glass of wine and it cost us £90. Every time I pay the bill for a teppanyaki dinner, I vow never to come back and year after year the kids beg to come back for the show which obviously made the meal delicious to them.  Benhihana does the teppanyaki show well and kids and groups will enjoy the experience. It seems fully booked all the time so there is certainly an audience for it. But it is not good value for money, and the food is uninteresting and bland (even with their sauce options). If the kids have a great desire to go then we may consider going back, but never for any other reason.

review_data.review_title: Not hugely impressed and very expensive
review_data.review: This is a very pretty restaurant on the beachfront at the Anantara hotel. The location and set up is very nice, and having a meal beside the beach with the crashing waves in the background is very romantic and soaking with atmosphere and style.  Service: The service was exemplary as expected at an Anantara. Attentive, helpful, and unobtrusive. They were kind enough to help move us inside to the air conditioned space which helped when it became too hot. They explained much of the dishes to us as well which was nice. When we left they got us a buggy to the reception and called our hotel and asked them to send a buggy to collect us. We were very impressed and pleased with this.  Food: The menu is very limited with only a few options for starters, mains and desserts. I was hoping for more seafood dishes and options. Their hallmark dish was seafood cooked on top of salt bricks. Heating the bricks and cooking it on top allows the seafood to absorb some of the flavour of the exotic salts. It felt gimmicky and I could not really taste any great benefit. I ordered the prawn version and it tasted like regular grilled prawns and was nothing special. I hoped to have some of the famous Thai flavours and passion reflected in the food. But I found the meal a bit bland. Don’t get me wrong, the food was fresh and all was very well executed but the mains were really not that interesting. The salt sommelier was there to assist with different types of salt to enhance your meal. I am a fan of interesting salts but again, this felt a bit forced. I could barely tell the difference between the salts and quite frankly, didn’t care. I just wanted to really good, tasty seafood. The starters were very good – most especially the rocket and pear salad which was quite WOW but a very small portion. The desserts were nicely made but nothing extraordinary. There was also a seafood feast but for the price, did not seem well worth it.  Price: This place was very expensive. I dont normally mind paying for good food but this felt unnecessarily expensive for what it was. I love Ananatra as a hotel and frequently dine at their restaurants even when I am not staying with them but the pricing of the is menu felt much too expensive for the food you were getting. Even if the price were lower, I would not be keen to come back again as I don’t find the food (except the salad) worth the inflated cost. It is a rarity that I do not like an Anantara establishment but the balance of value for money for atmosphere – made me feel disappointed.  I would not go back again for dinner as nothing interested my taste buds. I would not mind to have a drink or light snack there but as a dinner, I felt I could get better food, variety and price at one of the other dining options on the hotel property.

review_data.review_title: A worthwhile visit for drinks and soup
review_data.review: We had walked around the inner city areas before a thunderstorm and heavy rainfall mid / late afternoon. We were seeking refuge from the rain and cold and enjoyed a drink and bun here. A vibrant busy little bar area.  It was very busy but we wer3 att3nded to by friendly courteous staff. It was a good result here for about 75 minutes in a warm comfortable location.  Happy to recommend

zojuist NIEUW Hi..i have been yesterday for the first time..WAUW ...what a great service the guys give me..I liked the Nargile and the Food..When you are in Istanbul please come te here to enjoy your holiday..i will be back guys..thank you for everything

We visited the restaurant in Chelsea. The ambiance is energetic and you can immediately feel that it is a place for friends and groups rather than a romantic dinner with your partner. The show is funny and the food is well cooked but not exceptional because it's not elaborated. I suggest it for a different experience but not as usual place to go.

review_data.review_title: Firt time dining at Pure Thai
review_data.review: Four of us really enjoyed Pure Thai entrees. Dry Ratchaburi, Soup Sukhothai and the Pad Kee Moa w/chicken. The service was very good all the way around. Seating, server and delivery of our food. We especially enjoyed the drinks Hibiscus and Thai Ice Coffee. The desert topped off our mean Punkin Custard. The restaurant is small, so be prepared to share a table with others at lunch time when it's busy. We will be back to try other entrees, next time in area. Thank you.

chose to visit here knowing that the pizza and pasta were housemade and therefore no GF options available. however there were plenty of other options and i had a divine squid dish. great range of italian wines and the smells from the pizza oven were sensational!!!

Visited here with a group of teenage boys - no one was hungry afterwards! Ribs and steaks both very good, garlic sizzling mushrooms divine. Fairly pricey menu but on par with other similar establishments around the area.

Little Blackwood is a gem of a bar. They a great wine and beer selection and the cocktails look awesome too. The staff are always lovely and friendly and the live music gives it an awesome atmosphere!
very nice poke place in Hanoi. established menu or create your own. a good number of options to make it.highly recommended!!!

review_data.review: We came here for the cocktails. And we have not been disappointed. They not only look great - they taste good as well.
Spent one night here and enjoyed it. If you‘re in the area it‘s worth checking out and have some nice drinks.

As with a lot of the bars and restaurants in Marrakech this is on the roof of the building with views across the city. They also have a tea room/restaurant down stairs, although you don't get the views. We visited twice in our four days, once for a much needed liquid pitstop and the second time for dinner as the food we saw on our first visit look wonderful. The menu isn't huge but there are plenty of dishes to choose from. They also have a menu of the day priced around 100dhr which is unbelievable value for three courses and tea. a special shout out to our waiter Ismail, who assisted and guided us to our food selections. The food was excellent and extremely tasty.

I took my colleagues to RikaRoof for a nice diner. I had been there before, so knew what a great place it was. The menu is divers, with great appetizers, main courses and delicious desserts. Our waiters Baris and Ozgur provided excellent, friendly service. We enjoyed the sunset and view over old Istanbul so much! We'll be back in Istanbul in June and for sure pay Rika a visit again.

review_data.review: Really lovely little cafe to chill in and enjoy good food. It's attached to a training school which teaches pastry and other skills to young people which is a great cause.  The food are coffee are first rate, service was excellent and the setting is so peaceful.

review_data.review_title: Quality Italian food at this prestigious venue
review_data.review: It is many years since our last visit to Theo Randall - the place has been brightened up considerably since our last visit and although the low ceiling will always remain it is not so noiticeable.  The restaurant features a regional menu which at £50 including wine is excellent value for money - tonight's was from Emilia Romagna but our prefernce was from the wider A la Carte which is priced by the dish.  Starters of Minestrone and a Cheese souffle were both filling and delicious and mains of Pappardelle and Sea Bream very enjoyable. We finished with a shared Italian cheese course followed by a lovely soft chocolate cake.  The wine list is a lovely tour of Italian regions but there is a nice choice of wines by the glass enabling us to try a selection, the Jermann Pinot Grigio and Planeta Chardonnay both superb examples.  Service was friendly and efficient and we were much more impressed than on our previous visit.

review_data.review_title: Best views in town, hands down
review_data.review: My wife and I decided to try this place out for lunch, as we had heard it could get busy for dinner. Our first impression when we arrived on the top floor was: wooooooow! What a view!  You get a perfect view of the blue mosque and hagia sophia from their outdoor patio. It is simply stunning.  But enough with the view, we're here to eat after all! And eat we did. This place has traditional Ottoman palace cuisine, which is simply decadent. We had lamb stuffed with pine nuts and raw almonds, which was so tender and tasty. We also had slow-cooked lamb wrapped in eggplant, which was melt-in-your-mouth good.  We were two very satisfied travelling Canadian foodies that afternoon!

review_data.review: The creme brulee with pineapple is the best! Friendly and efficient staff. The Manager Christopher speak french as well, makes it easier to order. Easy to find on the corner of W 45 St and 5th Avenue.

review_data.review_title: Overall, a good experience, but expected better food and wines
review_data.review: This is a “closed door restaurant” for a maximum of 10 diners served on a communal table. The food was as described on the SaltShaker site- decent home cooking. But other than the soup, none of the dishes were that great. The accompanying wines weren’t anything special either - just common, everyday wines in quality. The experience was more about being in somebody’s home and sharing conversation with a small group of people from around the world. At the price $80/pp plus tip, we found much better value elsewhere in Buenos Aires.
Inside Le Bristol, Le 114 Faubourg is an elegant restaurant with a very good menu and an excellent wine list. Service is second to none.

We visited V Zatisi for a valentines meal with wine pairing and enjoyed it. I ordered the zatisi degustation and somehow ended up with the Indian one, but by the time I realized it, didn’t want to make a fuss. My son ordered the seasonal degustation and enjoyed it very much. Wine pairings were with generous pours, excellent whites and ok reds. Food presentation was good, Indian courses were tasty, the other courses a bit less flavorful. One star off because one of our dining partners ordered the steak and it was tough, requiring a lot of sawing to cut. Our wait staff were friendly with a great sense of humor, and overall we enjoyed the meal. Not sure we would return, as the price point was a bit high for the food quality.

Visited again, and took family this time. Enjoyed the brussel-sprout pizza and meatball pizza. The former is my favorite, and the latter was a special that day - with freshly made meatballs and sauce. Both were excellent. Although the server told us that the pizza's were "individual size" - do not be fooled - these easily feed two. The four of us didn't even finish the two pies. The place does a high volume of deliveries - which leads me to believe they have a very large following of repeat customers.  One negative is that the tables are kind of small.

Excellent restaurant and has to be among one of the best breakfasts to be had . Sea view is amazing . Seating and ambience is Very good. Food is awesome and staff are really helpful and great.  I love the bircher muesli, oatmeal, french toast and the halal egg station which cater well for muslims .  The staff. Kik, Jeejar, York, Phon, Kong, Soh, Ladda, Nancy, Dada and Ilya are just really awesome to see at the morning time .

review_data.review: We could not get a table at our hotel's Gourmet Corner restaurant at Le Siesta Diamond so the staff kindly recommended that we tried the Red Bean restaurant at their sister hotel at Le Siesta Central, a 10 minutes stroll. They made the reservation on our behalf and even escorted us to the restaurant - that is what I called 'good customer service'.  The Red Bean restaurant is situated at the foyer of the hotel and nicely laid out with a small bar. The ambience was good and the staff was attentive.  There is a lot to choose from the Menu, a combination of local Vietnamese and European food. As we have been in Hanoi for a few days and sampled quite a few local dishes, we decided to go for steak. We had tomato Rossini and fried vegetable spring rolls for our starters, followed by a tenderloin steak and a mushroom and aubergine claypot as our main courses. The food was gorgeous and very well presented. The portion size was just right for a fine dining. We had a flambe banana with ice cream and fresh fruit platter for our desserts.  We were not disappointed with the quality of food and service provided by yet another Le Siesta hotel which speaks volume for the Elegance Hotel Group. 3 of the EHG hotels have a Red Bean restaurants.  We were very pleased with our meal and thoroughly enjoyed our meal at the Red Bean and well done Le Siesta Diamond for recommending this restaurant.  Highly recommend that you give the Red Bean restaurant a go when you happen to be in the Old Quarter in Hanoi.  The Wise-Ones April 2019

review_data.review: The Gourmet Corner restaurant is on the 12th floor of the Le Siesta Diamond and Spa hotel in the Old Quater offering a fine-dining experience to hotel guests and the general public.  Great ambience with soft lighting and attentive staff. It offers a variety of choices from both local Vietnamese and European dishes. We had spring rolls, mango salad, soups, hot stone beef stew, fried chicken and fresh fruits.  We also had lunch on two occasions which were equally good and we have lighter dishes from the menu. The Wise-Ones April 2019

The only very slight improvement is maybe take the empty plates away a bit sooner. I think it was out of the staff's politeness and they didn't want to interupt because just a quick glance over and you could catch their attention. Very attentive and I would recommend this restaurant.

review_data.review_title: Quality service is the cherry on top of quality food
review_data.review: Lovely food and amazing service.  We sat on the sheltered roof terrace and watched the sunset over Siem Reap. The atmosphere in the restaurant was fabulous, loads of foliage decoration.  The food and drinks were really good quality and very good value for what you get. We also got a dessert. 2x mains, 2x drinks and 1x dessert was just under $40. What made it was the service, staff were super friendly, professional and courteous.  I would 100% recommend.

review_data.review: Better than ban mi 25. Taste of char siew, ham and the tastes baguette is very good. Would highly recommend and would go back again

review_data.review_title: A great quant restaurant in NYC
review_data.review: For one of our company events, we rented out the restaurant starting at 3pm, and then had appetizers served as we held our meeting (and drinks). At the conclusion of the meeting, we moved to dinner. The service staff was excellent, always stopping by and seeing how we're doing. The food was great as well as the presentation of the food. And the restaurant was clean and had a great feel to it. There were two sides to the restaurant, and even though we rented out part of it, the other side was still able to sit about 10-12 tables. It's also at a great "and active" location so you can get a true feeling on NYC as you enjoy your dinner.

The room is, I suppose, hip. Which means it's crowded, noisy and semi-shabby. The tables are too close and the banquettes are extremely uncomfortable. Cold wind blows in from the door because there is no vestibule.  Food was good, not great. Good list of French wines.  We started with charcuterie and cheese plate. About on par with Boar's Head cold cuts and supermarket cheese-counter cheese. Nothing special, nothing especially French and pricey at $31.  I ordered the lamb. After 30 minutes of waiting, the waiter came back and said "we're out of lamb." Huh? After 30 minutes? Anyway, I ordered the cheeseburger which was made with short-rib meat and was tasty. But nothing French about it at all.  We then ordered dessert: Tarte tatin (apple pie of the south of France), classically served with vanilla ice cream. The waiter came back, this time after 15 minutes, and said they're out of vanilla ice cream. Again, Huh? He offered to serve it with chocolate ice cream. Well, both the pie and the ice cream were fine.  So... OK food but not special. Inept service. Unappealing, loud room. Expensive for what it is.  We won't be back.  The next day we went a fabulous Fench Bistro called Le Parisien in the East 30's. This is what Dominique should aspire to be.

review_data.review: Very small spot but the best pizza I ever had in restaurant. Visited with friends to try this special pizza . Ordered sprouts pizza and regular .. I can eat at this spot everyday ..... A++

We had crepes here as a light dinner after a hectic day of walking. We loved the crepes! The kids loved their Nutella with ice cream and we tried the strawberry crepes with granolas. The dark chocolate sauce on the strawberry crepes with the combination of granola is superb! Next time, I need to try their savory/salgados crepes! Oh, not to forget - sweet potato french fries.  For us another plus is that we have vegetarian options.

review_data.review_title: Small pastry school cafe worth supporting- freshest croissants in town!
review_data.review: My daughter and I enjoyed the quiet atmosphere and enjoyed a coffee and croissant. Menu is based on the home baked fresh pastry and very cheap ($2-3). Quiet atmosphere set in simple surrounds just a short walk from Lucky Mall. Ideal for breakfast and a slow start to the day. The pastry school equips and trains young women with skills to cook quality cakes and pastry. My daughter loved the banana and ginger cake ! The cafe is up a narrow lane way that is easy to miss, but is signed.

review_data.review_title: Quality well priced menu in professionally run restaurant school.
review_data.review: Good venue with large capacity for dining upstairs or downstairs. Situated on a quiet stretch of the Siem Reap river a few minutes south along the river from Hard rock cafe. Food quality excellent as was the service and as a teaching school for hospitality students , you know that the profits are going to a good cause and well worth supporting this. Large groups should book ahead . We were able to walk in at lunch but was still busy so best to book ahead.

As we entered the property we were ushered to La Sala restaurant, at first glance this location is something to behold. We decided to enjoy our high tea Al fresco style by the tranquil tropical lagoon with its ancient Banyan tree as the centre piece. Cha Yam Bai is served in a towering beautiful bird cage of sweet & savoury bites. There is a fine collection of gourmet sandwiches, scones with jam & clotted cream and array of decorative desserts followed by tea & coffee. The cost of this experience was THB 15000++ thoroughly worth every cent, to spend the afternoon of classic indulgence. Enjoyed immensely relishing in the peaceful surrounding. Table 33 - It was the perfect location

Located in Turtle Village, we came to this restaurant so we could watch the NRL game and grab a bite to eat. The staff were amazing in trying to get the game on a screen where we were seated. We arrived for happy hour which was timed well with the match. Tai made sure we had drinks and food for the game. The pub serves authentic "Mexican" dishes as well as traditional Thai meals. We selected the Mexican food and the servings were very large and tasty. Prices are reasonable and service was excellent with a great atmosphere. We even had a game of shuffle board. Will definitely be back.

review_data.review_title: A Fine Dining Experience Not To Be Missed
review_data.review: Sea Fire Salt is an exceptional fine dining restaurant. We visited the restaurant three times during our Phuket Sandbox stay. Each time our dinner was cooked to perfection by the lady chef and her colleagues. Staff are attentive but not intrusive. In fact they enhance the experience with their relaxed and friendly manner.  To the food. In a word amazing! From the amuse bouche, the appetisers, the main courses and ending with an imaginative dessert, all were of the highest quality. Our personnel favourites - the beef tenderloin, the lamb chops and the sea bass both cooked on salt blocks - were cooked to the highest standard and were mouth-wateringly good.  If you stay at the Anantara please visit this excellent restaurant.

review_data.review_title: Exceptional food and service! And best Soufflé!
review_data.review: As a regular visitor to Paris, I decided to try this restaurant with our family who were visiting us in London.  From the moment we were greeted at the door to the moment we left the restaurant, we received fantastic service. Staff were so friendly!  The décor of the place is interesting. Some parts nice whilst others a tad on the tacky side but still a nice ambience.  The Scottish beef was amazing as was the chocolate soufflé. It was all perfection.  I was very impressed with this restaurant and I would definitely go back!

review_data.review_title: Great Argentine food at great prices
review_data.review: This place is the real deal: great genuine Argentine food, friendly service, nice ambience and very reasonable (non tourist) prices. I am an Argentine living in the U.S., so I know! We were in Buenos Aires for a week and despite the countless restaurants in the Palermo area, we just had to go back to this restaurant twice.  Try the classic "provoleta" as a starter. It is an Argentine staple, as is the chicken milanesa as a main course. For those who like something sweet and new, try their mashed sweet potatoes. They are not the same root vegetable as eaten in the U.S. It's sweeter and more fragrant. The dulce de leche pancakes for dessert are a great way to end a fabulous meal. I hope you enjoy it as much as we did!

review_data.review: Last year we visited the area and ended up at another well known burger shack. Later that day we stumbled upon Bill's. It looked so appealing and smelled heavenly from the sidewalk. I made a mental note & planned on visiting on our next trip to NYC for the holidays. Fast forward 1 year and here we are at Bill's Bar & Burger!  Upon arrival, we walked inside and found the place pretty packed. We were asked IF we had made reservations and the answer was "no". So, we were expecting the worst. However, we were told to head on down the steps and meet the hostess at the bottom of the stairs to be seated. At the bottom, no one was waiting for us. So we approached the hostess stand and got in line there. We explained that we had been sent down from upstairs. After a few minutes we were seated at a HIGH top and given menus. I was a little concerned about the HIGH seats since we had 2 small children in our party, but there were no other seats available at the time. A waiter was around and said he would be with us shortly. We waited and waited and waited. Finally, we see the waiter ask someone else to wait on us. It seemed like chaos.  We ordered 2 burgers and a basket of the sweet potato waffle fries. We also ordered a kids hotdog, which is a foot long! It came with a side of regular french fries and a kids beverage for $10. A regular burger runs around $13 and does NOT come with any sides. Add bacon for an upcharge.  It took about 35 minutes from the time we walked through the door to the time our food was arriving at the table. Everything looked amazing. Burgers were plump, juicy and oh so flavorful. Delish! Bacon was amazing. Regular fries were very tasty, crispy on the outside yet fluffy on the inside. Sweet potato waffle fries were disappointing. They had great flavor but were thin and turned out oh so crunchy and crispy. We asked for a new basket that was not overcooked. Well, we ended up with a second batch of crunchy fries.  Overall, we had a really good meal at Bills Burger & Bar. The burgers were really good. The kids enjoyed the hot dog & so did we since we had to help eat the foot long dogs. Regular fries were good, although they are probably frozen and not fresh cut. Sweet potato waffle fries were a miss. Prices were a tad high, but we expect that in NYC near Rockefeller Center. Dining room area was OK. It felt cramped and I was NOT crazy about the high top tables (for kids or adults). Downstairs seating felt like a basement, where as the upstairs was little more airy with a bar-pub overtone. Restrooms were clean, but one of the toilets kept leaking water on the floor. Staff was friendly. Service is a tad on the SLOW side. So, do not go if in a hurry. I would recommend. I will be back, but next time I will make reservations in hopes of getting a booth or regular table instead.  Bottom Line: Excellent burgers. Well worth a visit if in the area. Would recommend and will most likely be back next Christmas!

review_data.review_title: Rare location to eat, best steak ever!
review_data.review: Both of us had 30 day aged steaks with 4 sides of vegetables and sauces plus a bottle of Yarra valley (Victorian) cab sav which complimented a sensationally rich meal. Expensive by Balinese standards but outstanding in every way. Outstanding kitchen, service, management, ambiance and set up. Service was top notch and dessert were large but first class as well. Overall an outstanding experience and a new experience for us after may visits to Bali. If you can afford at least $100AUD a head to get the best steak ever, it’s worth the effort. Highly recommend.

review_data.review_title: Very scenic spot for a drink
review_data.review: We didn't eat here but spent most evenings having a cocktail overlooking the beautiful reflection pool and out to the Anderman sea to watch the sunset. Very polite and attentive staff. Great hammocks, tastefully done, Lange comfortable chairs and lounges to recline in, very tropical, very relaxing. Great spot to view the bi weekly fire show.

review_data.review_title: Excellent food and decor but mob of teenagers outside the restaurant harassing tourists for money ruined the evening.
review_data.review: The food and decor at this place are excellent, with live musicians in the front room. This place is a little gem. It’s very unfortunate that it is hard to find and if you are not accompanied by a guide or a local, you are followed by a mob of very aggressive teenagers who harass and threaten you until you give them money. We had a staff member from the restaurant standing a couple of meters this happened who just watched and did nothing to help. This is frankly appalling from the restaurant staff. The restaurant knows full well that the mob outside is vile and aggressive and they know the place is very hard to find on your own, but they didn’t offer to come pick us up from our Riad or anything when we called to book a table. It’s only when we complained on arrival that they offered that one of the waiters walked us back to our Riad after the meal. We give 1 star just because of this incident. Moroccan police don’t seem to care about these sort of things and the restaurant turns a blind eye. We will never return and we advise people to go either with a taxi or accompanied by a local for safety.

My friend and I were staying in the hotel and decided to go for cocktails in the Park Room!! It is a beautiful room with a lovely atmosphere!! I believe the server who was looking after us was called Altay and he was absolutely fantastic!! He kept checking our drinks were ok and also on our food when we decided to get dessert!! He was very friendly and kept us laughing and enjoying our evening!! The cocktails I had were absolutely delicious and I’d definitely be back for more!!

A cute little place hidden inside an alley of the old quarter, which is cool. It’s not easy at all to find vegan food around here so I was extremely happy I found this place. Very generous portion, reasonably priced, the mock meat taste so great, above all the story of the owner is sweet and moving. Defo become a regular visitor myself at this place.

review_data.review_title: Super Lamb and super price of $45 also they deliver for $8
review_data.review: Pros: Great value, great food, big portions, friendly folk cons: website doesn't say delivery so you can get it delivered for $8 which is worth it.  1 is enough for 2 people. Seriously. We are hungry guys and massively over ordered but have been enjoying the lamb for a couple of extra days.

Dinner was a delight. Yes, it is a little touristy, but the food and the service are superb. The warm vegetable mezza was the best. Our entree's were well-presented and very tasty. You can't go wrong eating here.

review_data.review_title: Just soooo simple and soooo good!
review_data.review: Maybe the best food in Times Square?! Two tacos was plenty of food for dinner and it was like $12! There are no chairs here, just standing bars. The atmosphere is fun and the tacos are absolutely fantastic!

Super efficient, polite & easy to deal with for delivery to a Villa in my case. All done via WhatsApp & paid cash when delivery arrived. Delivery super efficient & burgers, fries, chicken wings all really good. Family all happy & content.

Comfortable and pleasant place. Food is well presented and tasty. Very relaxed beachside vibe. Live music not too obtrusive but also engaging. Compact but decent wine list too. Helpful and friendly staff.
What a find. Excellent food & presented very well. Kind & attentive staff. Good value. Recommended. Book to be safe.

How on earth can you charge 21 dollars for a Margherita? I am italian and I know how much pizza costs to make. I also know that outside Italy pizza can be very "posh" but this is robbing people. Never again

review_data.review_title: Excellent service, great food and wine
review_data.review: As soon as we entered the attention to service was great, we had a lovely table upstairs, busy but not crowded, a good atmosphere. Quiet expensive but a great treat and memory. Waiters were very attentive but not an intrusion. All in all a great evening.

review_data.review_title: Food was good but service was poor
review_data.review: We dined at this Thai Restaurant when visiting Queenstown.  Nice venue and our table overlooked the street below.  I ordered a shared Seafood Tom Yum , Coconut Prawns and a Tiger Beer.  I waiting some time and my drink hadn’t arrived so I followed it up. She had forgotten??  Our Tom Yum arrived and it was large and very good. The Coconut Prawns we ordered had not arrived and this was also followed up. She said this wasn’t ordered? My wife and I heard the order made.  So the order taking left a lot to be desired.  We finished off with fried banana and ice cream which was a huge serve.

We were staying in Queenstown and had lunch at this venue at Steamers Wharf.  The view from our table was great towards the lake.  Service was attentive and friendly from our male servers.  I had the Sirloin with creamy peppercorn sauce and my wife had the Lamb Skewers. We shared a eye fillet salad.  All of our meals were excellent.

I had the pleasure of visiting New Hope as part of a recent business trip. The food was excellent, as was the service. The New Hope project is providing some wonderful opportunities within the local community, and i would definitely recommend anybody visiting Siem Reap to pay a visit for themselves .

review_data.review_title: The best Neapolitan Pizza in Brooklyn
review_data.review: These guys have done their homework, imported the oven and flour and have dedicated themselves to the art of Neapolitan pizza-making. Simple and perfect! Crispy, chewy crust, slightly wet center, fresh tomato sauce and cheese. You can't go wrong at Sottacasa. The wine list is short but affordable with a number of drinkable options. The backyard space is terrific on a warm night and the whole place seems to glow with warmth on cold evenings. Highly recommended after ten plus visits..

review_data.review_title: Full of tourists who use TripAdvisor, but the food is good

It's quite a few steps to get there, so if you are not inclined to do some random exercise, skip this.

Wouldn't mind coming back to this place again :-) and order something new every time we visit. Portion sizes are family style, so dine big with a group of friends!

review_data.review: We made a reservation for our anniversary. We were treated wonderfully and the food was very tasty. We loved our dinner and would eat here again for sure.

review_data.review_title: Great fresh food and excellent service
review_data.review: Went on our first day in Prague to grab some take-away for the family. It wasn’t fast, but that’s because everything is made fresh. And you can taste it! I have been to many Indian restaurants and this was top quality. Service was excellent and very friendly. Great!

review_data.review_title: Amazing experience, super friendly staff and great food
review_data.review: Overall an amazing experience. Located in a beautiful setting in Prague, on the river front, opposite the bridge. All staff spoke impeccable English and were professional and friendly. We ordered a Czech wine, recommended by our server which was excellent, and had a mixture of starters including the gem salad and shrimps. All portion sizes were more than enough for one person. For the mains again a selection of the ribeye steak, Czech 7 hour duck and Octopus. All meals were cooked to perfection. The price was also very good for the level of restaurant. Overall I cannot fault it. It was an amazing experience and we would definitely return. Thank you to all the staff for making it such a great evening, especially with the birthday surprise for my sister in law

review_data.review_title: One of our best meals in Paris
review_data.review: Our dinner at Aspic was one of our best meals in Paris. The space is intimate--probably holds about 30 guests--and has clean, simple lines. The only option is a pre-determined tasting menu, with the chef asking about any food allergies or dislikes when the reservation is secured. Our meal included 7 or 8 courses, with 3 of fish. The food was meticulously prepared and beautifully presented, but more importantly, many of the courses qualified as sublime. There were no misses. The price is beyond reasonable. They have an amazing selection of gins from France. We tried several G&Ts to start and loved the more floral one.
