review_data.review: The Edge is at "the edge" of the Palm, not far from the western pool and the games area.  I was served by Ekene who was friendly and chatty. He brought my drinks and food quickly and attended to me all evening until the bar shut.  On this point, it shut early, with last orders around 18.45 and most of the bar packed away by 20.00, on this week day Monday.  There were families around me who, it seemed, were looked after and it is an easy walk back to the west wing of the hotel.  You can just about see the fountains from here, and the view of the hotel through the palms is amazing.  Certainly take a little stroll out here.

Found this restaurant on TripAdvisor. They serve good food to a very reasonable price. Nice clean restaurant to high western standards. Very friendly service. The only drawback is that its difficult to find for the average tourist.

We’ve searched everywhere to find the best Thai food on Phuket. There are some very good ones but best to our opinion is Dee Plee. Top quality authentic Thai food for reasonable prices (compared for what you get). The staff could be a bit more attentive and look a bit better to their guests but … the kitchen make this more as good again. Highly recommended for quality Thai food seekers.

We chose Las Canas after scrolling through Trip Advisor and reading some good reviews. The food is ok, nothing to fave about and there are much better options for steak in s similar area. The pasta was fine but again nothing to special. Staff are friendly and welcoming although our waiter didn't speak English he was very accomodating with us and our limited Spanish. It's nice for a quick cheap dinner however would say the nice service outweighs the quality of the food.

This restaurant is part of a training hotel. The staff are students in training in the hospitality industry and they do their jobs spectacularly well.  I had the privilege of having had lunch here in February 2015. The service was excellent and the food awesome. Sala Bai is near the top of my "to revisit" list when I return to Siem Reap in future.

Visited this resort restaurant and was pleasantly surprised by the quality of the food and attentiveness of the staff. Be careful when asking for Spicy as the hot is hot! Food was top and the service from Yoo was very good. Not very busy which added to the experience. Seeing lightning inn the distance yet being sheltered from the rain made the evening.

review_data.review_title: Not that this restaurant needs another 5* review...
review_data.review: ...but I'll add to it anyway!  My friend surprised me with a visit here for my birthday, me a vegetarian and her very much a carnivore. The food is incredible! So many amazing flavours and the chef has clearly put a lot of thought into how the dishes all go together.  Not only is it delicious, but it is greatvalue for money. £20pp gets you the grande selection - a tapas-style offering of nearly everything on the menu. It's more food than we could eat (and boy did we try!). Favourite dishes included the cashew cheeze, the homemade pakoras and the two curry dishes.  You get free top ups of any dish you want (we couldn't manage that) and they give you doggy bags to take away your left overs. The vegan brownie we had for dessert was TO DIE FOR. Oh how can it be so rich and crispy and gooey all at once, and accompanied by delicious vegan ice cream.  You bring your own booze but we also tried the delicious complimentary tea at the end. They were also kind enough to give us little pots of the tea mix to try at home!  The atmosphere was warm and welcoming, with everyone cooing when their selections arrived, and the staff were incredibly lovely and helpful.  This is a gem in Earlsfield and I'll definitely be back, bringing friends (veggies and non-veggies alike) so that we can feast again!!

Had New Years eve dinner at this restaurant. It was a set tasting menu for the evening, absolutely delicious, everything we had was amazing. Hats off to the chef, it was truly great. Would definitely recommend this restaurant to every Prague traveler.

My husband invited me to Pur' to celebrate our first anniversary :) The whole experience was delightful from start to finish. We went for the 6-course dinner, which is very generous if you also count the beautiful amuse-bouche sent by the chef (we started with a foie gras lollipop which was divine!!). The bread and wine selection are exquisite, (a wine is associated with every dish), the service is outstanding and the food is mouthwatering. Every course was a beautiful surprise for our palates, and, for the cherry on the top, we met the chef before leaving and he gave us little cookies to take home and eat the next day. I will definitely be back on my next visit to Paris!

This was our first time at 114 Faubourg and we enjoyed everything enormously. The ambience is warm and relaxed, and the service we received was attentive and courteous at all times, from everyone. We took a la carte (rather than a tasting menu) - crab starters, monkfish for my wife and duck for me. All excellent, and my wife's avoidance of gluten and lactose was dealt with as no problem at all. Worth its star, and worth a visit. We'll go back.

review_data.review: My fillet which was meant to be medium was definitely well done and the lobster claws were undercooked. When the waiter/waitress was informed she said that sometimes this happens when the claws are big??? Really what kind of an excuse is that. Come and get sick....

review_data.review_title: Views are amazing, food was nothing special
review_data.review: We also ate here on our last night in Istanbul having had some great meals (and views) in our 5 night stay. The view here is stunning, overlooking pretty much all of Istanbul - panoramic views! We hadn't booked, but got a table on the terrace looking out over hagia Sophia museum. Waiters were efficient but took time to take our order as were having pictures taken with a group of Australian ladies! The food was good, we both had lamb and it was cooked really well , but nothing spectacular in terms of service or presentation of the food. We also tried a mojito - probably one of the worst I've tasted! I'd recommend for the views alone!

Tucked inside Blue Karma's Nestling Hotel you might miss this if you didn't know it was here. It has a large menu with a huge variety of food. My husband loved the Nasi Goreng and I fell in love with the chickpea and feta burger. The staff are attentive and always available
Burger was nice. I have had better but also a lot worse. Not a 5 out of 5 but easy a 4. Onion rings not great, chili mayo is spicy. Good price
Went there with my wife. Nice place with tasty food. Think the service could be better, it felt a bit stressed. Overall satesfied, but also had better experiences.

review_data.review_title: More than just a first class training restaurant
review_data.review: I have had many many meals at this restaurant as a volunteer at New Hope Cambodia and I have never had a meal I didn't like. Coffee Banana shake is to die for, Red Chicken curry is a must, too many to list. Great value for money, awesome service. A+++

review_data.review: Lovely Restaurant within this fabulous Hotel, we've experienced the breakfast,lunch & evening meals and they're all excellent, the flavours in the Thai curries are amazing. All the staff are so friendly & helpful & have made our holiday one to remember especially Toon & Eve who are such lovely girls, thank you for everything..x
Great wine and cheese experience. Chinmau was a fantastic server. Highly recommended for wine pairings that actually work

I cannot recommend this restaurant highly enough! After a week of tagine and couscous, it was wonderful to find a restaurant in Marrakech that served foie gras (poelee), confit de canard, filet de boeuf, lamb chops etc. The decor is quirky, with a “pseudo-industrial” feel, but the staff are efficient, enthusiastic, and all speak good English. The prices are not cheap, but the food quality is outstanding, so one leaves highly satisfied. We are not cocktail fans, but this is clearly a major attraction of this restaurant, indeed many people apparently come here just to drink them. The couple at the table adjacent spent several minutes photographing their cocktails before drinking them!

We were simply told to make a reservation here so didn't know what to expect, which made the experience even greater for us. Lovely location and set up, lovely staff, Luis is super friendly. My one fault that didn't give the night an 'excellent' rating was that the steak wasn't as juicy and succulent as others I've had which was disappointing for us. But a great night nonetheless :)

I've never eaten dinner on a swinging bed before but there's always a first time! We were met from the Tuk Tuk with a cool towel which was a nice touch. An excellent dinner (we had the tasting menu) that surprised at every course. Not cheap at all but great quality and as is usually the case, you get what you pay for.

We first went to their restaurant on Spring Street, which is very small & extremely noisy, so noisy we left and went around the corner to their, mainly, fish restaurant. I had the spagetti Nero with Langoustines and zucchini flowers. The sauce was lacking in flavour and was very peppery. They must have run out of zucchini flowers (already at 1:30pm) because there were none. My wife had the wild boar meatballs with porcini mushrooms and truffles. Both meals were okay, but not top notch Italian/Sicilian. They have very few Sicilian wines, and a lot of Tuscan / Piedmontese, which is probably understandable in the US. Sicily does have a lot of great wine producers so perhaps they aren't available here. They did have one Planeta rose, which is good, but for a popular choice Plumbago would be good. Work needs to be done in the kitchen & on the wine list, then perhaps they will live up to the name they created.

I hope this restaurant survives, it is a tough market but we thought they were doing everything right and I would definitely return next time I am in Paris.

Went to this place to have dinner after a Long day, and boy was I impressed. We had a crispy spring rolls to start with, and they were amazingly crispy and the filling tasted great. I had the panang chicken with rice, and the gravy tasted like good old home cooking, it paired really well with the rice. My friend had the Lok Lak Beef, which tasted really good as well, savoury and peppery sauce covered the tender beef slices. The ice lime tea was very refreshing in the humid weather. I would recommend this establishment to anyone seeking an authentic, well prepared meal at reasonable prices.

White chocolate mousse was a little dense and pistachio panda cotta was a little loose but tastes great. My wife had the dessert sampler, creme brulee, chocolate mousse and raspberry sorbet which she said ticked all the boxes. The praline and macaron petit fours rounded the meal off nicely. This is not my usual type of restaurant and way above what i normally pay but i didn't feel conned by the price and felt the whole experience was worth the money.

review_data.review_title: Mostly good but room for improvement
review_data.review: I visited twice in December, once by myself for lunch and again for lunch with hubby.  The first time I visited I had to go to the counter to ask for a menu. I sat down thinking they would bring a menu but I changed tables as I was too hot where I originally sat down. I wasn’t brought a menu at either table so I thought they didn’t have table service and you had to order at the counter by the cakes. When I asked if I could see their lunch menu they said they’d bring it over. Perhaps they didn’t see me come in but my first impression wasn’t that good. I know it’s not a big thing but nevertheless it’s nice to be greeted and brought a menu within the first few mins of entering a cafe/restaurant. Perhaps it would be better just to leave the menus on the table.  On my first visit they had run out of the vegan quiche. I understand cafes run out of food but it was a little bit disappointing since it was only around 1pm which is peak lunch time. Luckily, I’m not vegan I just like to eat vegan sometimes but from memory there weren’t that many other vegan choices so this may be a problem for others.  On my 2nd visit I was able to order the vegan quiche and my husband ordered a veggie one. Unfortunately, the vegan quiche had mustard seed and I’m allergic to mustard so I had to swap with my husband. It wasn’t written on the menu so I didn’t know before ordering. It would be nice if this info was added to the menu. I took one bite before I realized. The vegan quiche was not as tasty as the veggie quiche which contains dairy so perhaps a little tweak of the recipe might be in order.  We ordered 2 coconuts and one was nice and chilled and the other one completely warm.  On the 2nd visit we were brought menus straight away but our waitress silently took our order and also didn’t say anything when she brought our bill which my husband commented on. He thought perhaps she didn’t speak English. My husband is a local so she could have used Khmer if she preferred.  I understand this is a training school cafe so I’m writing this as constructive feedback so that others can have a more seamless experience.  The points above wouldn’t stop me from visiting again but there’s room for improvement.

review_data.review_title: Not many choices for lunch but the choices they do have are tasty
review_data.review: The only choices for the mains is cold pasta. I wasn’t sure what I’d think of the mango pasta but it wasn’t too sweet and great as a main dish.

review_data.review_title: Business lunch menu is superb value for money
review_data.review: I visited Chi restaurant with my cousin and his wife for lunch. We ordered from the business lunch menu. It is extremely good value for money considering the quality of food, ambience and service.  You can get 2 courses for $12 or 3 courses for $15 including one glass of wine or a soft drink. I found out about the business lunch menu from other TA reviews.  Unfortunately, we couldn’t afford to visit Chi restaurant for tasting menus that they offer in the evening but this was perfect.  The manager Sarah even came to introduce herself during our meal.  I would definitely like to visit again with hubby.

review_data.review_title: Smooth service for the most part

The duty manager came to speak to us at the end of our meal to check our dining experience which I appreciated. Eating at the training restaurant allows them to continue training students and I would definitely eat there again.

Hubby and I decided to try this new cafe since I noticed it was getting a lot of good reviews. The service was good without being overbearing and the staff checked with us if the food was ok.  They have a good selection of Khmer and Western food as well as juices and coffees. 2 mains and a green juice set us back $11.50 which I think was reasonable given the portion size and quality of the food. I would like to visit again, it’s just a shame it’s not open later on in the evening.

My husband and I had dinner here 2 nights ago. The ambience and presentation of the food was nice but the colourful sauces were more for decorative purposes than for taste which was a shame. Maybe it just wasn't to our taste.  The chive dumpling dish was better but the sauce for the veggies was so spicy it was a struggle to finish the dish.

review_data.review_title: Reasonably priced food in a beautiful garden setting
review_data.review: The price of the food was reasonable considering the beautiful setting of the restaurant. $10.50 for 2 meals and a drink. We were served fairly quickly and the service was friendly. I would definitely visit again.

review_data.review_title: Need to bring ID if not staying at the hostel
review_data.review: We visited last Friday evening.  The night didn't start off well as the security guard watching the motorbikes told us we couldn't come in because my husband is Khmer.  I started to feel my blood boil but luckily another staff member came and said we could come in but we had to go talk to reception (we weren't planning on staying, we just wanted dinner and a drink)  At reception, a lady who was a bit more knowledgeable than the security guard explained that since you have to walk past all the hostel rooms (3 floors) to get to the Sky bar where the bar/restaurant is, they need to take a copy of ID cards for Khmers and a copy of the photo page in the passport for non-Khmers to know who is coming and going for the safety and security of the guests at the hostel.  Once this was explained properly in a polite manner it was not a problem. I still find it a bit strange though as I normally don't carry around my passport when going out for dinner but luckily hubby had his ID card which meant that he became a member and could bring in a guest, me. So, it all worked out ok in the end. It's just a shame that the new security guard (we were told he was new by the other member of staff) is turning locals away.  As with most things here, it is an easily solvable problem. I don't know why they can't put up a big poster saying "ID card (for Cambodians) or passport (for non-Cambodians) needed to enter the premises for the safety and security of guests and visitors. We appreciate your co-operation."  After all, they had a poster saying their restaurant was closed but still welcome to order food at the bar, so they are capable of making and putting up signs.  The food was surprisingly good for a hostel. It was No.1 on TripAdvisor about a month ago and I was curious about it so suggested to my husband that we go.  Luckily, the nice female member of staff (didn't catch her name) and the good food managed to turn the evening around but just be forewarned that if you're not a guest you'll need ID to be able to go into the bar/restaurant area.

review_data.review_title: Tasty new Indian restaurant in town
review_data.review: I decided to visit based on the other positive reviews and to check out the new Indian restaurant in town. I am a big fan of paneer dishes. I ordered the paneer tikka masala which was delicious and they were generous with the paneer which I appreciated. The mango lassi was also very tasty. Pricing is similar to other Indian restaurants in town but I would say Rasoi Ghar is one of the better Indian restaurants that I’ve tried in Siem Reap and I’ve tried a fair few.

We had our first ever meal in South America at Cabernet based on the advice of our driver, and we were not disappointed. The chorizo appetiser was massive, but beautiful and very juicy - better even than Don Julio’s. The sirloin in red wine reduction was superb, and the waiters coped very well with our complete lack of Spanish, and request for a gluten free meal. The wine choice was spot on and the service generous, professional and warm. Seating options are inside, or a lovely covered adjoining courtyard facing a fabulous lovely street.

review_data.review: I will start with the setting, which was lovely. Outside dining with blue and white tones, over looking the ocean (if you are there before sunset). Their online reservation system is VERY broken. We had a reservation for New Year’s Eve (we received an email confirmation) but when we showed up, they had no record of it. They informed us that they were not doing the menu that night and sent us on our way - where are you supposed to find another restaurant at 9 pm on New Year’s Eve? We decided to try again on January 2nd. Again made reservations online...and received an email confirmation. Got to the restaurant and they had no record of the reservation...at least this time they accommodated us. As I said before, a lovely setting. Our waiter had some struggles providing us with accurate menu information (actually was inaccurate on his description of several menu items) and overall the service was fair at best. If you are looking at their menu online - DON’T! It is not the same....and the menu at the restaurant was not descriptive - hard to know what you were going to get. We saw nothing served on a salt block. I am wondering if they have changed management or the menu compared to previous reviews - usually Trip Advisor is a good reflection of a restaurant- but not this time - look only at recent pictures and reviews! Most items were very overpriced! We had Tiger Prawn Cocktail - it was only 2 (two!) prawns and cost 750 Bhat! They were good, but really? We ordered two bottles of wine that were listed in the menu for 1700 bhat and we were charged 2000 bhat per bottle! As for main dishes- the ribeye was fair at best, the scallops were 4 scallops - very tender but otherwise very average...the best dish we had was the blue swimmer crab - 4 crabs, very tasty but a lot of work to eat. The Parmesan mashed potatoes were good, enough for two people. The Lobster Mac and Cheese? Not an accurate description at all...it was more of a pasta in a lobster bisque - no cheese to speak of. We ordered asparagus - sorry, they were out. So, I don’t usually tell people to avoid a restaurant - but we had much better meals and experiences in Phuket- eat elsewhere!

I'm really glad we opted to try Steaks by Luis. We made the reservation about a month in advance of our trip to Buenos Aires, which was a stopover on the way to Ushuaia and our Antarctic expedition. As many reviewers have already mentioned, it's one of those "closed-door" restaurants that is in a fashionable loft and only takes place a few times a week. No sign - just a staff member outside to assure you you've found the place! My boyfriend and I actually walked from our hotel to the restaurant (we needed the exercise to help burn off the calories) - about 4.5 miles (7.25 KM)! We made just in time and were welcomed in to find appetizers (cheeses and cured meats) and a sparkling wine. We had some time to mingle and meet the hosts and to view the meats that would be grilled up for our other courses - deliciously beautiful! At a certain time (a little after 9 p.m., I guess) we were instructed to take our seats. We sat down across from an American couple who - it turns out - were heading out on the same Antarctic expedition we were booked on and had posted on a TA forum thread we started! And the couple to my right (from China) were also on the same ship! I would say that pretty much all 20 or so guests were either from English-speaking countries or spoke English so, while you probably won't meet many locals at SbL, you will have plenty of people to talk to! In fact, as in our case, you never know who you might meet! I actually loved the communal dining aspect - it made the time spent at dinner that much more enjoyable.  The food was amazing. We had a salad with cheese and apples along with a nice wine for the second course. The third course was the most interesting: a mixed grill of identifiable sausages and other meats, plus a few that were *mysteries* to some of the diners. They want you to try before you judge because many people avoid certain parts of the cow/pig on principle. Haha. Some of it I liked, some of it I didn't; everyone had an opinion, but most people were game to try all of it. Plus, they served a grilled provolone cheese that was amazing.  The steaks - the main course - were large (12 ounces); I couldn't even finish mine! It came with a side of garlic mashed potatoes that were scrumptious. But I made sure to leave room for the dulce de leche cheesecake, which was both beautiful and heavenly to the palette. Mmmm, mmm! Did I mention we had wine with all these courses? And it just kept magically refilling?  All in all, this is an experience you won't regret and I think it is actually a really great value for the attention and service (and food) that you get. It is a 3+ hour meal during which you will never be bored!
Visited in the afternoon and the lounge was really quiet. Had a few different drinks on offer and food was adequate. Sandwiches really good.

The food is always exceptional and creatively prepared using fresh regional ingredients. Each of 5 courses is described in detail and paired with thoughtfully chosen wines. review_data.review_title: Truly the highlight of our trip to Buenos Aires
review_data.review: We had a fantastic time from the moment we arrived. The description of what to expect was precisely accurate. We really enjoyed meeting the other guests but the food was the star of the show. Every dish was attractively presented and absolutely delicious. The portions were perfect if not slightly large but everything was seasoned to perfection. The chef Dan brings vast food knowledge from years of experience, research, and from being a food writer. This is such a special experience that I strongly suggest you book it in advance as to not be disappointed if trying to do so after you arrive in Buenos Aires. When available, Dan also provides food-oriented day tours. We were lucky to spend a full day with him and it enriched our experience immensely as he has lived there for almost 20 years. His Spanish and English are perfect and he speaks several other languages.
Worth the wait. The long line was no lie to the great dinner. The prices are right and the flavors are great. We will definitely return during our next visit to NY.

review_data.review_title: Pleasant food in a lovely location with good service.

We visited this brand new restaurant after we had heard of it from friends.  I remember this restaurant used to be "U Cervena Tabulka", and it is amazing what they have done with the place, you will not recognize it. They have a new bar area, and an incredible beverage selection  The food was simply out of this world. We all tried two dishes, which were all good. I had veal and my wife ordered lamb. This guy knows the menu and helped steer us into a superb meal. If in Bali and you aren’t a vegetarian then you just have to spend the money and enjoy the experience. It’s not cheap and a night out for two will cost you about $250 to $300 AUD but we’ll worth every cent.

Great Italian food, pizza’s are incredibly thin and eggplant entree is superb. Enjoyed the wine, very attentive service maybe just bordering on overwhelming at times. Great night out and reasonably priced.

As per the title of this review the food and service were fantastic. I personally didn't love the space which was quite dark and cramped so I feel this would be more of a winter dining destination (as it is cosy) than a summer one. We would have liked to check out the bar too but did not manage to do that on this occasion. I think, when we dined here previously (many years ago) that we had our meal on the upper level where the bar now is. I was keen to try some cocktails and was told that not all cocktails made in the bar were available in the restaurant and I wasn't sure why but that's ok. I did have 2 very nice cocktails whilst there (pink diamond and a dessert cocktail as I had no room for dessert after the amazing entree and main).
